Free AI
-------

The web does, of course, include lots of free content, much of which accrue=
s to Google=E2=80=99s benefit: Wikipedia, Reddit, blogs, etc., are themselv=
es user-generated content but on the open web. Lots of other free content, =
though, was monetized by ads, produced by publications employing profession=
al writers. This was an inherently difficult business, though, thanks to th=
at free distribution: that meant there was infinite competition, which mean=
t the only route to profitability was continuing to cut costs.

What, then, should we have expected to happen once the world gained the mea=
ns of generating human-level content at zero marginal cost? From Futurism (=
 https://futurism.com/sports-illustrated-ai-generated-writers ) :

There was nothing in Drew Ortiz=E2=80=99s author biography at Sports Illust=
rated to suggest that he was anything other than human. =E2=80=9CDrew has s=
pent much of his life outdoors, and is excited to guide you through his nev=
er-ending list of the best products to keep you from falling to the perils =
of nature,=E2=80=9D it read. =E2=80=9CNowadays, there is rarely a weekend t=
hat goes by where Drew isn=E2=80=99t out camping, hiking, or just back on h=
is parents=E2=80=99 farm.=E2=80=9D

The only problem? Outside of Sports Illustrated, Drew Ortiz doesn=E2=80=99t=
 seem to exist. He has no social media presence and no publishing history. =
And even more strangely, his profile photo on Sports Illustrated is for sal=
e on a website that sells AI-generated headshots, where he=E2=80=99s descri=
bed as =E2=80=9Cneutral white young-adult male with short brown hair and bl=
ue eyes.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=A6

According to a second person involved in the creation of the Sports Illustr=
ated content who also asked to be kept anonymous, that=E2=80=99s because it=
=E2=80=99s not just the authors=E2=80=99 headshots that are AI-generated. A=
t least some of the articles themselves, they said, were churned out using =
AI as well.

What makes this article particularly poignant is the property involved: Spo=
rts Illustrated was an icon of the print era; it transitioned to the web so=
mewhat, in a partnership with CNN, but over the last several years is has l=
aid off staff and passed from hand to increasingly unethical hand. Unethica=
l, that is, if you prioritize journalistic integrity over making money: it=
=E2=80=99s hard to escape the sense that the two are irreconcilable. Journa=
lism costs money, which means an uncompetitive cost structure, and Sports I=
llustrated isn=E2=80=99t the only one. Continuing from Futurism:

As powerful generative AI tools have debuted over the past few years, many =
publishers have quickly attempted to use the tech to churn out monetizable =
content=E2=80=A6We caught CNET and Bankrate, both owned by Red Ventures, pu=
blishing barely-disclosed AI content that was filled with factual mistakes =
and even plagiarism; in the ensuing storm of criticism, CNET issued correct=
ions to more than half its AI-generated articles. G/O Media also published =
AI-generated material on its portfolio of sites, resulting in embarrassing =
bungles at Gizmodo and The A.V. Club. We caught BuzzFeed publishing slapdas=
h AI-generated travel guides. And USA Today and other Gannett newspapers we=
re busted publishing hilariously garbled AI-generated sports roundups that =
one of the company=E2=80=99s own sports journalists described as =E2=80=9Ce=
mbarrassing,=E2=80=9D saying they =E2=80=9Cshouldn=E2=80=99t ever=E2=80=9D =
have been published.

These, of course, are the companies that were caught; in time, the AI will =
become good enough that no one will know what is real and what is not.

